      "role": "user",
      "content": "but that's the thing... if you look at the actual history, the founders' intent was clearly about protecting rights from government infringement. if the court is ignoring that to make modern laws, isn't that just objectively failing its job? it feels like calling it \"dynamic adaptation\" is just a polite way of saying they're making up the law as they go. don't you think there's a real danger when you stop looking at the actual text and history?",
